WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.040
Welcome everyone to today's webinar.

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:18.000
We're going to talk about reproducible examples from a conceptual point of view and why they're

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:23.760
surprisingly important, and then also a great deal from a mechanical point of view, how

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:29.280
to make your reproducible examples in a way that they're easy to share with other people.

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:36.919
This short link, the rstud.io reprex, I promise it will always point to something very relevant

00:00:36.919 --> 00:00:41.360
to this package that will link to absolutely everything else.

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:47.200
So the first thing I want to do is show basic usage, and we're just going to get right into

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:51.060
it and then we'll unpack what you just saw.

00:00:51.060 --> 00:00:57.799
So I'm sitting here in an RStudio session, it's fresh, and I have a little bit of code

00:00:57.799 --> 00:00:59.840
up here in my source editor.

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:08.139
I'm going to make a factor X, a factor Y, I'm going to combine them and get what to

00:01:08.139 --> 00:01:11.480
most of us is kind of a puzzling result.

00:01:11.480 --> 00:01:17.540
So this is just going to be an example of a small piece of code that maybe you want

00:01:17.540 --> 00:01:24.680
to talk about on the community site or share with your local R expert and ask what's going on.

00:01:24.680 --> 00:01:31.180
So this is how you would use reprex to turn this little snippet of code into a reproducible example.

00:01:31.180 --> 00:01:35.620
This is the path of least resistance, we'll talk about other methods later.

00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:43.940
So I would select a little piece of code and copy it to my clipboard.

00:01:43.940 --> 00:01:52.000
And over in the R console, I'm going to type reprex.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:57.360
And you will see that that little piece of code is run.

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:03.000
And then basically a beautiful, attractive version of that is stored on my clipboard

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:04.800
and I can preview it here.

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:12.880
So if I were to paste the contents of my clipboard right now, you actually see what's called

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:19.720
markdown and this is what's necessary to create the attractive version of this code.

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:21.059
And why is this helpful?

00:02:21.059 --> 00:02:28.860
Because you can go to places like GitHub, the RStudio community site or Stack Overflow

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:31.300
and paste this markdown in.

00:02:31.300 --> 00:02:38.179
So I'm going to show you what this would look like in a GitHub issue.

00:02:38.179 --> 00:02:41.740
So that's that same markdown that you just saw.

00:02:41.740 --> 00:02:43.960
GitHub lets you preview things.

00:02:43.960 --> 00:02:47.520
And you'll see that it looks just the way it did locally for me.

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:50.080
It's been rendered, it's syntax highlighted.

00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:54.440
We have a tiny little ad down here that tells people how you did this.

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:58.720
And I could submit that as a GitHub issue.

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:03.539
So that is the basic process.

00:03:03.539 --> 00:03:13.059
And the reason I can just type reprex is that I always have this package attached.

00:03:13.059 --> 00:03:17.639
And so you might need to call this and we're going to talk a great deal about that next.

00:03:17.639 --> 00:03:21.460
So that is what basic reprex usage looks like.

00:03:21.460 --> 00:03:27.179
It creates a small little piece of code, renders it nicely, and it's ready to paste into other

00:03:27.179 --> 00:03:29.779
formats.

00:03:29.779 --> 00:03:36.339
So this is just a static version of what we just did.

00:03:36.339 --> 00:03:40.259
And this is the GIF that I use on the reprex website.

00:03:40.259 --> 00:03:42.020
I rewatched this clip.

00:03:42.020 --> 00:03:46.820
It's from a movie called Jerry Maguire, it's still highly recommended.

00:03:46.820 --> 00:03:51.660
And basically the reason for bothering to do all of this is if you're going somewhere

00:03:51.660 --> 00:04:01.020
to have a conversation about R, to have questions answered, or to describe a bug in software.

00:04:01.020 --> 00:04:06.380
Being careful about how you make your reproducible example makes it much, much, much easier for

00:04:06.380 --> 00:04:09.940
other people to help you.

00:04:09.940 --> 00:04:13.360
And I want to explain where this word came from, reprex.

00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:19.579
So Roman first tweeted this and I thought it was just a great made up word.

00:04:19.579 --> 00:04:22.820
So it is short for reproducible example.

00:04:22.820 --> 00:04:26.299
So it is a completely made up word.

00:04:26.299 --> 00:04:29.619
But it's just very handy.

00:04:29.619 --> 00:04:34.640
And I'm going to use the word reprex over and over and over again in this webinar.

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:40.779
So I want to be very clear that I'm using it in, I'd say, three distinct but related

00:04:40.779 --> 00:04:41.779
ways.

00:04:41.779 --> 00:04:49.100
So I think people, at least in the small R community, are starting to say reprex just

00:04:49.619 --> 00:04:52.619
as a noun, like it is a reproducible example.

00:04:52.619 --> 00:04:56.579
And that has nothing to do with whether you use this package or not.

00:04:56.579 --> 00:05:02.940
But then today's webinar is going to show you use of a package with that same name,

00:05:02.940 --> 00:05:05.420
reprex, that you can install from CRAN.

00:05:05.420 --> 00:05:08.299
I'll show you how to do that in just a moment.

00:05:08.299 --> 00:05:10.820
And then this is a pretty small package.

00:05:10.820 --> 00:05:17.619
It has a couple of functions, but really the main function it has is also called reprex.

00:05:17.619 --> 00:05:23.299
So this webinar is going to talk about how to use the reprex function inside the reprex

00:05:23.299 --> 00:05:28.019
package to produce a good looking reproducible example.

00:05:28.019 --> 00:05:30.899
And when does this come up in your life?

00:05:30.899 --> 00:05:38.660
It's very handy for conversations that you have on community.rstudio.com.

00:05:38.660 --> 00:05:45.660
It's very handy for preparing questions or answers for Stack Overflow.

00:05:45.660 --> 00:05:51.500
It's very handy for reporting bugs or making feature requests for an R package that is

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:54.579
developed on GitHub.

00:05:54.579 --> 00:06:01.820
And also very useful for having detailed conversations about R in Slack or in email.

00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:07.739
So a reproducible example, conceptually, is useful in all of those places.

00:06:07.739 --> 00:06:14.339
And then this package, reprex, smooths over some of the mechanics.

00:06:14.339 --> 00:06:19.299
So here I want to talk to you about what you're going to need to do on your computer to make this

00:06:19.299 --> 00:06:23.299
package available to yourself.

00:06:23.299 --> 00:06:28.579
So reprex does not come with R. It does not come with RStudio.

00:06:28.579 --> 00:06:32.220
You have to make an explicit effort to install it.

00:06:32.220 --> 00:06:40.420
So you should pick one of these methods, and it's the type of thing that you do once per computer.

00:06:40.459 --> 00:06:50.140
So you could use install.packages, open quote, reprex, close quote, to install just the reprex package.

00:06:50.140 --> 00:06:55.100
It is also part of the meta package that we call tidyverse.

00:06:55.100 --> 00:07:01.660
So if you did install.packages tidyverse, reprex would be one of the many packages that get installed

00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:02.779
on your machine.

00:07:02.779 --> 00:07:08.540
In general, there is very little harm that you can do to yourself by reinstalling packages.

00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:16.019
So you also should not stress out too much about, you know, you could install just reprex and then install

00:07:16.019 --> 00:07:17.899
the tidyverse and nothing bad will happen.

00:07:17.899 --> 00:07:24.220
So do it once per machine just because that's the minimum you need to do, but it's no tragedy if you

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:25.019
reinstall things.

00:07:25.019 --> 00:07:32.579
Once you've installed, you still need to use our sort of library call to make the reprex functions

00:07:32.579 --> 00:07:34.500
available in your R session.

00:07:34.500 --> 00:07:40.980
So you would need to do this in every R session that you plan to use reprex in.

00:07:40.980 --> 00:07:46.579
So that might be something that you do multiple times per day, certainly way, way, way, way more than

00:07:46.579 --> 00:07:48.019
once per computer.

00:07:48.019 --> 00:07:54.940
So every time you want to use the package, you'll need to execute the library reprex command.

00:07:54.940 --> 00:08:01.140
Now, I use reprex several times a day for the most part, and so that would be very annoying.

00:08:01.140 --> 00:08:08.619
So an alternative, if you also become a semi-heavy user of this package, is to make it available to

00:08:08.619 --> 00:08:11.260
yourself all the time.

00:08:11.260 --> 00:08:19.339
So you can control the startup behavior of R through a file called .rprofile, and conventionally, it's

00:08:19.339 --> 00:08:21.940
found in your home directory.

00:08:21.940 --> 00:08:28.100
And so this snippet of code, suppress messages require reprex, looks a little different from what you

00:08:28.100 --> 00:08:34.659
just saw, but it's sort of a better way to attach this package in your startup file.

00:08:34.659 --> 00:08:43.460
So you would put this snippet of code there in your .rprofile, and then forevermore, when you start R,

00:08:43.460 --> 00:08:46.619
the reprex package would be available.

00:08:46.619 --> 00:08:54.099
And if you have never thought about your .rprofile file before, there is a function in the use this

00:08:54.099 --> 00:09:00.020
package, which you would also have to install, that will create it for you if you don't have it.

00:09:00.020 --> 00:09:07.020
Or if you do have it, it would open it for you for editing in case you wanted to put something like

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:10.219
this snippet in there.

00:09:10.219 --> 00:09:15.500
So once you've done those two things, you've installed it and you've attached it through either the

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:23.700
library command or by putting something in your .rprofile, you are ready to use the reprex function.

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:31.140
And what you saw me do in that first demo was I actually called the reprex function explicitly in the

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:32.500
R console.

00:09:32.500 --> 00:09:38.340
And something you'll see me do before we're done is we also have put some what are called RStudio add-ins

00:09:38.340 --> 00:09:45.820
into this package that give you even more ways to launch this function.

00:09:45.820 --> 00:09:53.580
This is a bit of a sidebar, but since I have shown you how to put things in your .rprofile file,

00:09:53.580 --> 00:09:57.659
I also want to tell you how to do that responsibly.

00:09:57.659 --> 00:10:00.020
So reprex is a workflow package.

00:10:00.020 --> 00:10:04.940
It's something you would use in your daily work to make your life a little bit easier.

00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:07.140
You use it interactively.

00:10:07.140 --> 00:10:15.979
I would be pretty shocked to see it show up in a typical person's R scripts, R markdown files, packages,

00:10:15.979 --> 00:10:17.500
or shiny apps.

00:10:17.500 --> 00:10:23.460
And so the fact that it doesn't show up in those things, it's an interactive package, makes it safe

00:10:23.460 --> 00:10:26.219
to attach in your R profile.

00:10:26.219 --> 00:10:31.580
But I don't want you to get the wrong idea and think, oh, my God, I should do this with all my packages.

00:10:31.580 --> 00:10:39.539
So I would not want to see this kind of code using like dplyr or ggplot2 or things that do show up in your

00:10:39.539 --> 00:10:40.419
scripts.

00:10:40.419 --> 00:10:46.099
And it's because your scripts would then become highly not self-contained.

00:10:46.099 --> 00:10:51.340
And they would work for you because of stuff in your R profile, but they won't work for other people.

00:10:51.340 --> 00:10:58.460
So this is an interesting technique to know about, but you need to be really, really careful about what you do here.

00:10:58.460 --> 00:11:00.859
So I think it's safe to put reprex in there.

00:11:00.859 --> 00:11:03.020
It is not safe to put dplyr in there.

00:11:03.020 --> 00:11:07.340
Okay, so we're going to get back to the package and to reproducible examples now.

00:11:07.340 --> 00:11:16.219
So I wanted to give a brief intro, like what on earth in my life drove me to make this one of my missions.

00:11:16.219 --> 00:11:28.700
Before I joined RStudio, I was a professor at the University of British Columbia, and I had a course called Stat 545 that has a lot of content online to this day.

00:11:28.700 --> 00:11:31.260
The course continues, so you could go there.

00:11:31.260 --> 00:11:34.900
And I ran this course entirely on GitHub.

00:11:34.900 --> 00:11:46.140
And so it meant that all of my dialogue with students, both sort of me to the whole class and me talking to individual students,

00:11:46.140 --> 00:11:48.340
took place in GitHub issues.

00:11:48.340 --> 00:12:01.140
And I actually analyzed my GitHub usage in the course, and I found that every fall I was participating in at least 300, maybe 500 GitHub issue threads.

00:12:01.140 --> 00:12:04.460
And that's just in my teaching life.

00:12:04.460 --> 00:12:11.380
So I spend a great deal of time talking about R in those places and solving people's R problems.

00:12:11.380 --> 00:12:22.260
And to do that well, I actually wanted to use executable R code, and the friction involved in making that look good started to drive me crazy.

00:12:22.260 --> 00:12:34.780
And now that I'm no longer a full-time faculty member and I'm working full-time on R packages, this just gives you a sense of the intensity of my GitHub activity over the last year.

00:12:34.780 --> 00:12:40.059
So now I still work with tons and tons of GitHub issues, you know, in a different capacity.

00:12:40.059 --> 00:12:43.500
And then I also talk about R a lot in Slack.

00:12:43.500 --> 00:12:55.179
So I still have this sort of hourly need to run little pieces of R code and share what I'm seeing with other people.

00:12:55.179 --> 00:13:06.979
So trying to remove friction for myself and other people led me to create a few principles that I knew had to be true of a tool to make this easier.

00:13:06.979 --> 00:13:11.179
So this is the reprex philosophy.

00:13:11.179 --> 00:13:18.179
I think that conversations about code are much more productive if they contain three things.

00:13:18.179 --> 00:13:20.859
Well, it's one thing, but three properties.

00:13:20.859 --> 00:13:24.859
Code that actually runs, okay?

00:13:24.859 --> 00:13:33.460
Code that I do not have to run as the reader, but code that I can easily run.

00:13:33.460 --> 00:13:44.580
And so there is a little bit of self-contradiction here, but the point is you want to make it easy for people to interact with your reproducible example in a whole bunch of different ways.

00:13:44.580 --> 00:13:54.500
They can just be a consumer, they can just read it, or they can easily grab it and run it themselves, modify it, and share that back with you.

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:59.739
So I want to be really detailed about what I mean when I say code that actually runs.

00:13:59.780 --> 00:14:04.700
So you're going to isolate a little piece of R code and you hand it off to reprex.

00:14:04.700 --> 00:14:05.580
You've seen one demo.

00:14:05.580 --> 00:14:07.820
We're about to do a whole bunch more.

00:14:07.820 --> 00:14:17.979
That code is taken and it is run in a completely new R session, and that means it has to be completely self-contained.

00:14:17.979 --> 00:14:25.380
So it must include the command to load all necessary packages, and it must create all necessary objects.

00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:30.700
And this can be very frustrating for people, but it's extremely important.

00:14:30.700 --> 00:14:40.700
So I'm going to go do this live to show exactly what I mean.

00:14:40.700 --> 00:14:51.580
Okay, so I'm looking at an R script that contains the code you just saw on that slide, and I'm going to restart R.

00:14:51.580 --> 00:14:55.020
So let's imagine like a typical interactive R session.

00:14:55.020 --> 00:15:03.940
So I'm going to be down in the console here, and I'm going to say, oh, I'd like to play a little bit with this praise package I've heard about.

00:15:03.940 --> 00:15:05.219
So there I go.

00:15:05.219 --> 00:15:09.419
I say library praise down on the console.

00:15:09.419 --> 00:15:18.900
Now up in my source editor, I make a new object called template, and it's a template string exclamation.

00:15:18.900 --> 00:15:21.500
Your reprex is adjective.

00:15:21.500 --> 00:15:27.099
And so if I then call the praise function from the praise package, I don't expect you to know this.

00:15:27.099 --> 00:15:29.419
I'm just using it as an example.

00:15:29.419 --> 00:15:36.020
It's going to create like random little sentences for us praising someone for their awesome reprex.

00:15:36.020 --> 00:15:40.619
So let's say I want to share my joy about this with people using the reprex package.

00:15:40.619 --> 00:15:43.460
I would select this little snippet of code.

00:15:43.460 --> 00:15:46.500
Again, this is the long way.

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:48.099
I'll show you a short way later.

00:15:48.099 --> 00:15:56.940
Copy it, go down to the console, type reprex, and hit return.

00:15:56.940 --> 00:15:59.700
And now let's look at the preview here.

00:15:59.700 --> 00:16:04.140
It shows defining template, and then my praise call fails.

00:16:04.140 --> 00:16:05.299
Error in praise.

00:16:05.299 --> 00:16:09.219
Could not find function praise.

00:16:09.219 --> 00:16:15.580
And that's because you don't have the library praise command here.

00:16:15.580 --> 00:16:21.419
So over in that fresh R session, the praise package is not available to use.

00:16:21.419 --> 00:16:23.539
So here's something else you might do.

00:16:23.539 --> 00:16:26.739
You're like, okay, I'm going to add that command.

00:16:26.739 --> 00:16:29.979
Then I'm going to make my call to the package.

00:16:29.979 --> 00:16:31.099
Let's see if that works.

00:16:31.099 --> 00:16:37.099
Copy, call reprex again.

00:16:37.099 --> 00:16:38.059
I have a new error.

00:16:38.059 --> 00:16:40.219
Error in grep, whatever, whatever.

00:16:40.219 --> 00:16:42.739
Object template not found.

00:16:42.780 --> 00:16:46.419
So this snippet is incomplete in a different way.

00:16:46.419 --> 00:16:52.580
It actually doesn't contain the code that defines the template object.

00:16:52.580 --> 00:16:54.940
So here's the full snippet.

00:16:54.940 --> 00:16:59.500
It loads the praise package.

00:16:59.500 --> 00:17:05.099
It defines the template object, and it makes this function call.

00:17:05.099 --> 00:17:10.859
So I'm going to copy all of that to the clipboard.

00:17:10.859 --> 00:17:19.859
Re-execute reprex, and we have made an exquisite reprex.

00:17:19.859 --> 00:17:25.819
So that's a little belabored, but when I try to answer our questions for people,

00:17:25.819 --> 00:17:32.859
and I try to run their code, the two most common ways that I fail are

00:17:32.859 --> 00:17:37.699
that they haven't explicitly listed all the packages they're using,

00:17:37.699 --> 00:17:42.339
and I have to either sleuth it out of them or figure it out for myself

00:17:42.339 --> 00:17:47.219
and add those commands, or the objects they're referring to

00:17:47.219 --> 00:17:48.540
are not available to me.

00:17:48.540 --> 00:17:51.060
And so those are the two reasons why I can't run their code.

00:17:51.060 --> 00:17:56.219
So on the reprex website, I have a list of do's and don'ts

00:17:56.219 --> 00:18:01.459
that are distilled from a lot of other really fantastic sources

00:18:01.459 --> 00:18:04.939
about creating reproducible examples, which are referenced there.

00:18:04.979 --> 00:18:10.939
But the three big, big high points are you need to write this reproducible example

00:18:10.939 --> 00:18:15.979
using the smallest, the simplest, and the most built-in dataset

00:18:15.979 --> 00:18:19.780
you can get away with, and that is very uncomfortable for people.

00:18:19.780 --> 00:18:22.500
I'm going to talk about that in a second.

00:18:22.500 --> 00:18:28.180
Include commands on a ruthlessly strict need-to-run basis.

00:18:28.180 --> 00:18:31.979
So you really need to strip your example down.

00:18:31.979 --> 00:18:35.420
And then I say pack it in, pack it out, and don't take liberties

00:18:35.420 --> 00:18:37.260
with other people's computers.

00:18:37.260 --> 00:18:42.459
And this is referring to making sure that if you create files,

00:18:42.459 --> 00:18:46.459
you remove them, or if you change the working directory, you reset it.

00:18:46.459 --> 00:18:50.060
If you change options, you reset them, but basically leaving things

00:18:50.060 --> 00:18:52.500
as you found them.

00:18:52.500 --> 00:18:58.020
But I want to talk about, so let's see, here's what that web page

00:18:58.020 --> 00:19:02.819
would look like if you want to read it more.

00:19:02.819 --> 00:19:07.180
But let me just give a short example of something that a lot of people

00:19:07.180 --> 00:19:09.619
struggle with, which is that they feel like they have some big,

00:19:09.619 --> 00:19:14.819
hairy data object, and they can only show their example using it.

00:19:14.819 --> 00:19:20.380
So tricks to know, so the read CSV file you probably think of as normally being

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:26.099
a function that you use to bring data, sorry, the read CSV function is something

00:19:26.099 --> 00:19:32.859
you usually bring delimited data in from a file, but it also has a text argument

00:19:32.859 --> 00:19:37.660
that allows you to inline really tiny R objects.

00:19:37.660 --> 00:19:41.020
And then also just the data frame function itself.

00:19:41.020 --> 00:19:48.420
So I'm going to reprex using a keyboard shortcut those two snippets of code.

00:19:48.420 --> 00:19:54.060
And see, that's a very easy way to make a very tiny data frame either inline

00:19:54.060 --> 00:20:00.500
using read CSV or sort of from first principles using data frame.

00:20:00.500 --> 00:20:06.540
And then if you are a tidyverse adherent, the tibble package is what takes care

00:20:06.540 --> 00:20:12.300
of the care and feeding of tibbles, which are a flavor of data frame.

00:20:12.300 --> 00:20:17.420
And the tribble function is extremely useful for creating tiny little data frames

00:20:17.420 --> 00:20:24.099
because it allows you to write it in this really humane row wise way,

00:20:24.099 --> 00:20:27.939
like the same way it would look in, for example, in a CSV file.

00:20:27.939 --> 00:20:33.579
So if I reprex this little snippet, you'll see very, very similar output

00:20:33.579 --> 00:20:38.020
as what we just saw with the base function, but it allows you to inline the creation

00:20:38.020 --> 00:20:42.459
in this case of a two row, two column data frame, or you can, again,

00:20:42.459 --> 00:20:45.619
use just the tibble function directly.

00:20:45.619 --> 00:20:50.859
And so if you make a lot of reprexes, you get really good at figuring out how

00:20:50.859 --> 00:20:55.020
to inline the creation of very small objects.

00:20:55.020 --> 00:21:00.339
Of course, figuring out what's the smallest object that still shows your problem

00:21:00.339 --> 00:21:03.219
is difficult, and we're going to talk about that at the very end.

00:21:03.219 --> 00:21:08.500
Okay, another principle is that the reprex should contain code I do not have to run.

00:21:08.500 --> 00:21:13.699
Because a lot of your readers have a great deal of R experience.

00:21:13.699 --> 00:21:18.619
And sometimes, not always, but sometimes they can quickly see the point

00:21:18.619 --> 00:21:20.579
without actually running the code.

00:21:20.579 --> 00:21:27.060
But that is greatly enhanced if they can see the output instead of having to run it

00:21:27.060 --> 00:21:31.579
in their head and in their imagination and try to figure out what's happening.

00:21:31.579 --> 00:21:36.300
It's just much easier if you can actually see the output.

00:21:36.300 --> 00:21:41.140
And so that's why I think it's important that your typical reprex contains the code

00:21:41.140 --> 00:21:47.420
and it also reveals the output being produced by that code.

00:21:47.420 --> 00:21:54.699
So here's an example I took from the GitHub repository where the readr package

00:21:54.699 --> 00:21:59.859
is developed because it's a perfect little example, and it probably was produced

00:21:59.859 --> 00:22:01.180
with reprex.

00:22:01.180 --> 00:22:02.339
You can't tell.

00:22:02.339 --> 00:22:08.219
And this person is just reporting a bug, but it's like a great minimal example.

00:22:08.260 --> 00:22:13.699
It says, you know, if the header in your CSV contains quoted new lines,

00:22:13.699 --> 00:22:17.540
you get kind of a weird column name and you get weird data.

00:22:17.540 --> 00:22:23.819
And the fact that this person provided a small example and it completely shows

00:22:23.819 --> 00:22:28.060
the problem, I imagine, is what allowed the maintainer, Jim Hester,

00:22:28.060 --> 00:22:32.619
who's listening to this call, to quickly label this as a bug.

00:22:32.619 --> 00:22:35.819
And we've already got at least one other user giving it a thumbs up,

00:22:35.819 --> 00:22:38.099
meaning they've experienced it as well.

00:22:38.099 --> 00:22:43.420
And so if you would only have the code here, I think you'd have a lot less sort

00:22:43.420 --> 00:22:46.619
of quick engagement with this issue.

00:22:46.619 --> 00:22:51.219
Okay, so code that I can easily run is very important, and we're going to keep

00:22:51.219 --> 00:22:53.699
working with that issue.

00:22:53.699 --> 00:23:00.660
So if that person had instead copied and pasted the output from their R console,

00:23:00.660 --> 00:23:03.060
this is what we would be faced with.

00:23:03.060 --> 00:23:08.140
So if I were Jim Hester and I needed to reproduce this issue and make sure that

00:23:08.140 --> 00:23:13.939
it's still a problem, I have a lot of really annoying editing to do.

00:23:13.939 --> 00:23:17.699
So I have to get rid of all the prompts at the beginning of the lines.

00:23:17.699 --> 00:23:22.819
I have to get rid of all this output to isolate the three lines of code

00:23:22.819 --> 00:23:24.420
that actually do anything.

00:23:24.420 --> 00:23:29.859
So copy-paste from the R console hits some of our checklist, but it's not great

00:23:29.859 --> 00:23:35.420
because it's very hard for the next person to run this code.

00:23:35.420 --> 00:23:38.979
Worse than copy-paste is the screenshot.

00:23:38.979 --> 00:23:43.099
So this, of course, does, again, hit some of our checklist.

00:23:43.099 --> 00:23:45.140
It clearly shows the code and the output.

00:23:45.140 --> 00:23:49.739
But again, if somebody else wanted to check this and reproduce it,

00:23:49.739 --> 00:23:55.780
they actually have to retype everything, which, frankly, is never going to happen.

00:23:55.780 --> 00:24:01.939
And so this is what I want to see in a reprex because it can be copy-pasted and run.

00:24:01.939 --> 00:24:04.939
So I'm going to prove that to you right now.

00:24:04.939 --> 00:24:12.579
So if I go to this issue on GitHub and I copy, I could copy all of this or I could,

00:24:12.579 --> 00:24:15.780
as long as I get all the commands, I'm okay.

00:24:15.780 --> 00:24:18.020
So I'm going to put that on my clipboard.

00:24:18.020 --> 00:24:27.300
I'm going to go back to R, maybe to make this really explicit.

00:24:27.300 --> 00:24:28.619
I'll show you what I copied.

00:24:28.619 --> 00:24:30.260
All right, that's what I did.

00:24:30.260 --> 00:24:40.619
So I can copy this again and call reprex.

00:24:40.619 --> 00:24:45.900
And I get exactly what this person was reporting on GitHub.

00:24:45.900 --> 00:24:50.660
So I've been able to reproduce it very quickly from a copy-paste.

00:24:50.660 --> 00:24:54.420
But as you saw, reprex is like, are you sure you want to do this?

00:24:54.420 --> 00:24:58.260
Because I've got this output here.

00:24:58.260 --> 00:25:08.619
And so if you really want to get really clean code from a reprex that someone else has made,

00:25:08.619 --> 00:25:15.380
you capture it and use one of the undo functions in the reprex package.

00:25:15.380 --> 00:25:20.780
I could use reprex clean, and I'll show you that right now.

00:25:20.780 --> 00:25:22.420
So here's what I copied from GitHub.

00:25:22.420 --> 00:25:30.260
So I could copy that and call reprex clean.

00:25:30.260 --> 00:25:35.619
And now if I paste, you'll see all the output has been eliminated.

00:25:35.619 --> 00:25:41.300
And so I think that's a slightly obscure thing you might want to do.

00:25:41.300 --> 00:25:46.500
But there are the full set of backwards functions in reprex.

00:25:46.500 --> 00:25:52.699
So it helps you take code that people have copied from the console or that they have

00:25:52.699 --> 00:25:56.060
already made a reprex from.

00:25:56.060 --> 00:26:00.979
So we've gotten to essentially the meat of the webinar now.

00:26:00.979 --> 00:26:04.300
So if you were really interested in basic usage, you've seen it now.

00:26:04.300 --> 00:26:08.939
And now I'm going to go into the shock and awe section, where I run through a lot of

00:26:08.979 --> 00:26:15.619
more interesting features of the reprex package that I still think are pretty cool.

00:26:15.619 --> 00:26:21.020
So the slides show you what we're about to do live.

00:26:21.020 --> 00:26:26.060
I'm going back to RStudio, and I'm in a script called shock and awe.

00:26:26.060 --> 00:26:30.180
I'm going to restart R just for good measure.

00:26:30.180 --> 00:26:36.500
So the first thing I want to show you is how frictionless reprex can make it to talk to

00:26:36.500 --> 00:26:38.500
people about figures.

00:26:38.619 --> 00:26:45.939
So I'm going to load the Gapminder data and ggplot2, and I'm going to make a plot with

00:26:45.939 --> 00:26:46.939
ggplot2.

00:26:46.939 --> 00:26:50.180
So you see it down here in my plots pane.

00:26:50.180 --> 00:26:54.739
So let's say that there's something about this I don't like or that I want to discuss

00:26:54.739 --> 00:26:56.060
with a colleague.

00:26:56.060 --> 00:26:58.020
I can use reprex for this.

00:26:58.020 --> 00:27:08.780
So as usual, I can select the snippet, copy to my clipboard, and run reprex.

00:27:08.780 --> 00:27:14.380
You're going to see all the same stuff.

00:27:14.380 --> 00:27:18.819
So we've got a nicely rendered reprex that includes the figure.

00:27:18.819 --> 00:27:21.260
But watch this.

00:27:21.260 --> 00:27:28.699
I'm going to go to a GitHub repo that I created just to play around with.

00:27:28.699 --> 00:27:32.339
I'm going to create a new issue.

00:27:32.339 --> 00:27:39.060
I have a question about this plot, and I'm going to paste.

00:27:39.060 --> 00:27:40.060
Let's look at what we've got.

00:27:40.060 --> 00:27:47.099
We have the usual sort of nicely formatted markdown, and look at this.

00:27:47.099 --> 00:27:54.900
So when reprex rendered this code, it made your figure and pushed it up to Imgur and

00:27:54.900 --> 00:27:59.260
dropped this link into your markdown.

00:27:59.260 --> 00:28:08.459
So if I submit this issue, people see my code, and they see the actual figure that you just

00:28:08.459 --> 00:28:09.459
made.

00:28:09.459 --> 00:28:15.500
So this is an example of one of the cool things you can do that removes a tremendous amount

00:28:15.500 --> 00:28:20.619
of friction if you're trying to have a quick conversation with somebody about code that

00:28:20.619 --> 00:28:22.420
produces figures.

00:28:22.420 --> 00:28:27.780
OK, so we're going to go back to this shock and awe script, and we're going to execute

00:28:27.780 --> 00:28:34.939
reprex many times, showing some of the options and different arguments you have.

00:28:34.939 --> 00:28:41.540
So so far, I've only shown you reprexing when the source code is on the clipboard, but there

00:28:41.540 --> 00:28:44.300
are a lot of other ways to provide the input.

00:28:44.300 --> 00:28:52.280
So you can provide it directly in the reprex call as an expression.

00:28:52.280 --> 00:28:58.300
So here you see that the assignment of x and y gets done, and we compute the correlation

00:28:58.300 --> 00:29:00.219
between them.

00:29:00.219 --> 00:29:05.859
There's also an input argument that I'm actually not going to demonstrate where you can provide

00:29:05.859 --> 00:29:13.219
the source as a file or as a character vector.

00:29:13.219 --> 00:29:20.079
Reprex, by default, goes and does its work in the session temp directory.

00:29:20.079 --> 00:29:24.660
That's all part of it sandboxing all of your work.

00:29:24.660 --> 00:29:30.500
But if your reprex does, for example, file input and output, it could be much easier

00:29:30.500 --> 00:29:35.500
to force reprex to work in your current working directory.

00:29:35.500 --> 00:29:41.439
So out file equals NA is shorthand for that.

00:29:41.439 --> 00:29:50.599
So if I try to if I ask R to write the first six letters of the alphabet to a file without

00:29:50.599 --> 00:29:57.880
file equals NA, all of a sudden, these four files that reprex needs to create are being

00:29:57.880 --> 00:30:03.319
left behind in my working directory instead of in a temp directory.

00:30:03.319 --> 00:30:07.599
And it's the R script that reprex makes.

00:30:07.599 --> 00:30:16.439
It's the HTML that it uses for the preview and the markdown that it puts on the clipboard

00:30:16.439 --> 00:30:17.439
for you.

00:30:17.439 --> 00:30:22.800
So all those usual files are left behind in a much more accessible place, but you'll notice

00:30:22.800 --> 00:30:27.319
it has a godawful file name because we just created it out of thin air.

00:30:27.319 --> 00:30:33.640
So if you want to work somewhere specifically and have nice file names, you could also provide

00:30:33.640 --> 00:30:39.000
the base for that in out file.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:42.839
And now you see that it leaves the same four files behind, but they have a much better

00:30:42.839 --> 00:30:44.400
file name.

00:30:44.400 --> 00:30:51.959
OK, so so far I've been producing reprex output that's optimized for GitHub.

00:30:51.959 --> 00:30:55.459
So it's producing what's called GitHub flavored markdown.

00:30:55.459 --> 00:31:02.000
But stack overflow is another common target, and that produces slightly different looking

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:06.920
markdown.

00:31:06.920 --> 00:31:13.199
Stack overflow doesn't use fenced code blocks, it uses indented code blocks.

00:31:13.199 --> 00:31:15.599
And let me show you what this would look like.

00:31:15.599 --> 00:31:20.640
I'm going to pretend like I'm going to answer my own question on stack overflow, but I won't

00:31:20.640 --> 00:31:22.199
actually submit this.

00:31:22.199 --> 00:31:27.520
But now if you paste that into stack overflow, it also has a preview feature and it will

00:31:27.520 --> 00:31:34.959
be formatted correctly for stack overflow.

00:31:34.959 --> 00:31:40.239
You can also make reprex produce, it creates an R script, which seems sort of weird, but

00:31:40.239 --> 00:31:47.959
an R script that includes the output as comments, and that is very handy for pasting into an

00:31:47.959 --> 00:31:49.800
email or into Slack.

00:31:49.800 --> 00:31:54.760
So I'm going to show you the Slack version of that.

00:31:54.760 --> 00:31:57.239
So this is me talking to myself on Slack.

00:31:57.959 --> 00:32:05.599
I'm going to create a code snippet, paste it, maybe I always have it set to R, create

00:32:05.599 --> 00:32:11.839
a snippet, and that would create a little R file in Slack, properly syntax highlighted.

00:32:11.839 --> 00:32:19.739
And again, people could copy paste it into R and run it, or sometimes you just want to

00:32:19.739 --> 00:32:21.760
inline it.

00:32:21.760 --> 00:32:26.880
You don't get the syntax highlighting, but that also looks quite nice.

00:32:26.880 --> 00:32:32.479
The final venue I'll talk about is RTF for rich text format.

00:32:32.479 --> 00:32:35.040
And this is a very experimental venue.

00:32:35.040 --> 00:32:40.160
It only works probably on the Mac at this point, because I actually have to call an

00:32:40.160 --> 00:32:42.680
external utility to do this.

00:32:42.680 --> 00:32:47.599
But I'd like to show you this, and in fact, it's how I made the slides for this talk.

00:32:47.599 --> 00:32:56.319
So we run a little bit of code, but now I can go over to Keynote or PowerPoint or something.

00:32:56.319 --> 00:33:01.920
And I could paste that in, and I'm getting rendered R code that is properly syntax highlighted.

00:33:01.920 --> 00:33:08.400
And that is, in fact, how all the snippets in my webinar were produced.

00:33:08.400 --> 00:33:18.739
You can suppress the inclusion of that little ad at the bottom, or you can include it.

00:33:18.739 --> 00:33:24.939
You can ask for your reprex to include session info.

00:33:24.939 --> 00:33:31.699
And for the GitHub venue, it can be placed in this cute little collapsible thing.

00:33:31.699 --> 00:33:36.780
So this is a great thing to include if you think, for example, that the bug you're reporting

00:33:36.780 --> 00:33:41.020
could possibly be related to the version of software on your computer.

00:33:41.020 --> 00:33:42.699
And I love that it gets folded here.

00:33:42.699 --> 00:33:48.640
So then sometimes people include this when they don't need to, and it's kind of overwhelming.

00:33:48.640 --> 00:33:55.520
So the fact that we can put it in this folding tag is really nice.

00:33:55.520 --> 00:34:01.380
Reprex can also use the Styler package to restyle your code.

00:34:01.380 --> 00:34:07.280
So here's a really, I would say, poorly formatted piece of code.

00:34:07.280 --> 00:34:13.760
So by default, reprex trusts that you know what you're doing and that you like your formatting.

00:34:13.879 --> 00:34:22.080
But if you don't trust yourself, you can explicitly ask for reprex to restyle your code and give

00:34:22.080 --> 00:34:25.919
it a much more conventional layout.

00:34:25.919 --> 00:34:34.280
You can be silly and change your comment string and make it some sort of emoticon if you want.

00:34:34.280 --> 00:34:36.959
Reprex is part of the tidyverse, right?

00:34:37.080 --> 00:34:44.600
So the tidyverse meta package can be quite chatty at startup and tell you all the packages

00:34:44.600 --> 00:34:48.300
that you've just attached and if there are conflicts between them.

00:34:48.300 --> 00:34:54.639
So we actually have a special argument where you can control whether you want that or not.

00:34:54.639 --> 00:34:55.639
And usually you don't.

00:34:55.639 --> 00:34:58.000
So we default to silencing it.

00:34:58.320 --> 00:35:07.040
And then the last thing I'll show you is reprex can actually capture input that in an interactive

00:35:07.040 --> 00:35:11.080
session shows up in your console, but it's actually being sent to standard output or

00:35:11.080 --> 00:35:12.879
standard error.

00:35:12.879 --> 00:35:19.719
So I'm going to install a package from GitHub that requires compilation.

00:35:19.719 --> 00:35:22.159
This takes a moment, so I'm going to chat over it.

00:35:22.719 --> 00:35:28.320
But what you're going to see when this reprex actually renders is that we have captured

00:35:28.320 --> 00:35:32.919
everything that would normally show up in the R console when doing this.

00:35:32.919 --> 00:35:38.560
So the stuff that is sort of coming from R as well as the things that are being sent

00:35:38.560 --> 00:35:42.560
standard output and standard input.

00:35:42.560 --> 00:35:43.879
I was hoping that would be enough.

00:35:43.879 --> 00:35:44.879
There we go.

00:35:44.879 --> 00:35:45.879
Okay.

00:35:45.879 --> 00:35:50.760
So this captures the output of installing the bench package from GitHub, which does

00:35:50.760 --> 00:35:52.879
require compilation.

00:35:52.879 --> 00:35:57.239
And so this is the part that's coming through sort of normal R channels.

00:35:57.239 --> 00:36:05.320
And this is capturing what's being sent to standard output and standard input.

00:36:05.320 --> 00:36:10.280
So that was a very quick live demo of some of the more, I don't know if they're really

00:36:10.280 --> 00:36:14.760
advanced, but features you don't need in every reprex, but that you might need before long.

00:36:15.439 --> 00:36:20.520
A lot of the things that I showed you toggling on and off.

00:36:20.520 --> 00:36:25.800
You can actually set up your own personal defaults for these things by, again, putting

00:36:25.800 --> 00:36:29.439
some code in your .R profile, which we've already talked about.

00:36:29.439 --> 00:36:34.199
So this is just an example of someone who hates the ad.

00:36:34.199 --> 00:36:36.760
They always want to include session info.

00:36:36.760 --> 00:36:39.320
They always want to restyle their code.

00:36:39.320 --> 00:36:48.159
They have a whimsical sense of what the comment string should be for output, and they always

00:36:48.159 --> 00:36:50.280
want to see the tidyverse startup message.

00:36:50.280 --> 00:36:55.879
So these are not my defaults, but it's an example of what you can do.

00:36:55.879 --> 00:37:01.600
And the last thing I'll show you mechanically is most of the time I do not do what I've

00:37:01.600 --> 00:37:08.959
shown you, which is copying code to the keyboard and then going to the console and typing reprex.

00:37:08.959 --> 00:37:15.239
There are two RStudio add-ins that really accelerate your reprex life.

00:37:15.239 --> 00:37:19.199
One of them is called render reprex, which launches a GUI.

00:37:19.199 --> 00:37:21.360
I'll show you that in a second.

00:37:21.360 --> 00:37:29.080
Or reprex selection, literally reprex is the code that you have selected, and it's absolutely

00:37:29.080 --> 00:37:33.840
conceived for use with a keyboard shortcut.

00:37:33.840 --> 00:37:38.719
And RStudio lets you modify your keyboard shortcuts.

00:37:39.479 --> 00:37:43.360
And so I have bound that add-in to shift command R.

00:37:43.360 --> 00:37:45.600
This is how I usually use reprex.

00:37:45.600 --> 00:37:48.120
And for example, Hadley also uses it a lot.

00:37:48.120 --> 00:37:57.280
He has bound it to something else, and let me go show you the add-in.

00:37:57.280 --> 00:38:11.280
So again, I could select the snippet of code that made that figure and launch the add-in.

00:38:11.280 --> 00:38:17.360
And so this allows you to specify a lot of the things that you can specify in the call

00:38:17.360 --> 00:38:18.560
by clicking.

00:38:18.560 --> 00:38:24.320
So I'm going to take the source from the current selection.

00:38:24.320 --> 00:38:30.919
Let's target stack overflow, and yes, let's append session info.

00:38:30.919 --> 00:38:39.040
Click render, and the usual things happen, and the usual output appears down here.

00:38:39.040 --> 00:38:45.199
And stack overflow doesn't have the capability to support this little folding toggle, so

00:38:45.199 --> 00:38:48.919
the session info actually gets dumped in there, and it's full glory.

00:38:48.919 --> 00:38:59.120
So these are two other ways to get your input into the reprex function that actually are

00:38:59.120 --> 00:39:02.760
probably more humane than typing it all the time.

00:39:02.760 --> 00:39:06.679
All right, the last thing I'll say we have, I'll try to go quite quickly because we're

00:39:06.679 --> 00:39:12.959
already at 45 minutes, is talking a little bit about the human side of making reproducible

00:39:12.959 --> 00:39:13.959
examples.

00:39:13.959 --> 00:39:16.679
And now this has nothing to do with the reprex package.

00:39:16.679 --> 00:39:24.280
It's just about asking questions so that they actually get answered.

00:39:24.280 --> 00:39:30.120
And I like this image because it conveys somehow that, you know, we're talking about programming,

00:39:30.120 --> 00:39:34.360
maybe we're all supposed to be acting like robots, and people often seem to assume that

00:39:34.360 --> 00:39:40.719
they're talking to robots, but that there's a lot of humans involved in this process.

00:39:40.719 --> 00:39:44.840
And I want to warn you, I'm getting a little bit of tough love here.

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:50.879
There's been a lot of, although probably still not enough, talk of experts being empathetic

00:39:50.879 --> 00:39:57.840
to newcomers and question askers, but since this is a talk targeted at people asking questions

00:39:57.840 --> 00:40:02.840
and preparing examples, I also want to say it has to go the other direction as well.

00:40:02.840 --> 00:40:06.000
So bear with me for a moment here.

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:12.439
But I need to say, you know, with all the love in the world, sometimes people come with

00:40:12.439 --> 00:40:18.479
a question and they have like a very rigid theory about what's wrong or how they should

00:40:18.479 --> 00:40:21.280
be solving a problem.

00:40:21.280 --> 00:40:25.800
But if your theory about what was going wrong was so great, like you wouldn't be here asking

00:40:25.800 --> 00:40:27.520
this question right now.

00:40:27.520 --> 00:40:33.280
And this is the origin of why people really want to see code instead of having sort of

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:36.040
a prose discussion.

00:40:36.040 --> 00:40:41.280
Because it's very hard sometimes to tell what people are really talking about.

00:40:41.280 --> 00:40:46.879
The other life phenomenon I want to link this to is, I don't know if you've had this

00:40:46.879 --> 00:40:51.679
experience, but if you've ever tried to help, for example, one of your relatives sort out

00:40:51.679 --> 00:40:56.679
a computer problem over the phone, it can be extremely difficult.

00:40:56.679 --> 00:40:59.360
A lot of what they're saying doesn't really make sense.

00:40:59.360 --> 00:41:03.760
They don't use the words you're used to to refer to things.

00:41:03.760 --> 00:41:06.159
You just feel like you can't really get a grip on things.

00:41:06.159 --> 00:41:10.679
And this is basically what it feels like when you're trying to answer someone's programming

00:41:11.080 --> 00:41:14.280
question just based on English prose.

00:41:14.280 --> 00:41:19.800
And again, like this is why people constantly push you to actually just show a small piece

00:41:19.800 --> 00:41:20.800
of code.

00:41:20.800 --> 00:41:25.000
It removes all sorts of ambiguity.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:31.379
So let's assume that everybody, the question asker and the question answerer, is acting

00:41:31.379 --> 00:41:32.379
in good faith.

00:41:32.379 --> 00:41:35.560
And if they're not, then they're irrelevant to me.

00:41:35.560 --> 00:41:38.600
Okay, so everyone's in good faith.

00:41:38.600 --> 00:41:46.600
It turns out that experts posting on public sites actually are afraid to post code that

00:41:46.600 --> 00:41:48.320
doesn't work.

00:41:48.320 --> 00:41:54.080
And so another reason why these people want to see your code is, you know, they're not

00:41:54.080 --> 00:41:56.120
just reading it and guessing.

00:41:56.120 --> 00:42:00.320
Most of these people are actually running your code, proving that their proposed solution

00:42:00.320 --> 00:42:01.320
works.

00:42:01.320 --> 00:42:04.399
And then they post it when they know that it's safe to do so.

00:42:04.399 --> 00:42:06.399
And this was a big revelation to me.

00:42:06.399 --> 00:42:12.080
I really used to think that the people I looked up to as experts just knew all this

00:42:12.080 --> 00:42:16.760
stuff by heart, and they were answering all these questions just off the cuff.

00:42:16.760 --> 00:42:21.879
And then it gradually dawned on me that part of why they're experts or expert behavior

00:42:21.879 --> 00:42:27.639
is that they are constantly running lots of small examples and experiments.

00:42:27.639 --> 00:42:33.919
So sharing your problem in code is extremely fruitful.

00:42:33.919 --> 00:42:36.639
Solving a good reprex is a lot of work.

00:42:36.639 --> 00:42:42.219
Like sometimes you think I can only show my problem in my R session, and I haven't restarted

00:42:42.219 --> 00:42:44.080
R for seven months.

00:42:44.080 --> 00:42:47.760
And it requires the full data set from my thesis.

00:42:47.760 --> 00:42:51.439
And that is in fact true, it is a lot of work.

00:42:51.439 --> 00:42:54.800
But you're asking other people to solve a problem.

00:42:54.800 --> 00:42:57.600
And so this is part of meeting them halfway.

00:42:57.600 --> 00:43:00.600
But it turns out you get a lot out of this as well.

00:43:00.600 --> 00:43:03.080
So let's be very selfish.

00:43:03.239 --> 00:43:10.479
If you make a good reprex out of your hairy, messy problem, and if you reproduce other

00:43:10.479 --> 00:43:14.959
people's problems, even reproducing other people's problems is a real service.

00:43:14.959 --> 00:43:17.520
And then sometimes you're going to be able to solve them.

00:43:17.520 --> 00:43:24.719
It turns out this discipline, it's like playing scales or serving over and over again.

00:43:24.719 --> 00:43:28.639
You actually get better at programming by doing this.

00:43:28.679 --> 00:43:34.520
The last selfish point that I'll make is it turns out when you sit down to make a good

00:43:34.520 --> 00:43:40.159
reprex out of your problem, and you keep it self-contained, you strip down your giant

00:43:40.159 --> 00:43:45.360
hairy data set to the smallest data set that reproduces the problem, it is amazing how

00:43:45.360 --> 00:43:50.280
often you end up answering your own question in the privacy of your own home, and you didn't

00:43:50.280 --> 00:43:53.679
have to make yourself vulnerable to other people.

00:43:53.679 --> 00:43:56.820
So this is a great revelation.

00:43:56.820 --> 00:44:00.699
And I think the reason this works is that when you have a problem, it's very easy to

00:44:00.699 --> 00:44:04.419
just keep going in circles and banging your head against the desk.

00:44:04.419 --> 00:44:09.939
But there's something about preparing it for other people, and the reprex package is also

00:44:09.939 --> 00:44:14.659
being a real hard-ass about making sure that your problem is self-contained.

00:44:14.659 --> 00:44:21.379
It kind of knocks you out of that very unproductive place and gets you back on the path of actually

00:44:21.379 --> 00:44:23.600
working the problem.

00:44:23.600 --> 00:44:28.280
So most people report this when they first start making reproducible examples, is that

00:44:28.280 --> 00:44:35.639
it's kind of amazing how often this exercise means you actually answer your own question.

00:44:35.639 --> 00:44:40.040
I will skip over this section since we're out of time, and I didn't think people wanted

00:44:40.040 --> 00:44:45.620
to know it, but it's here, a little bit about what's happening behind the scenes.

00:44:45.620 --> 00:44:46.620
And I will conclude.

00:44:46.620 --> 00:44:52.600
I want to give a huge thank you to Yi-Hui Zhe and all the people who have brought us

00:44:52.600 --> 00:44:56.760
the R Markdown package and Pandoc.

00:44:56.760 --> 00:45:02.719
The reprex package is just a wrapper around those things, and I mean that in both senses.

00:45:02.719 --> 00:45:05.919
Like, that is literally all that it is.

00:45:05.919 --> 00:45:08.479
So in some sense, there's not much there there.

00:45:08.479 --> 00:45:12.840
But on the other hand, when I first made it, and then especially now that I've worked on

00:45:12.840 --> 00:45:16.560
it more, there's actually a lot more going on.

00:45:16.560 --> 00:45:21.360
Like, the friction that it removes is friction that is really important to remove, I think.

00:45:21.360 --> 00:45:25.679
So in any case, it could not be possible without R Markdown and Pandoc, and in fact,

00:45:25.679 --> 00:45:30.159
I should thank all the co-authors of reprex, and there's a lot of people who have contributed

00:45:30.159 --> 00:45:35.239
to it and a lot of users who've been extremely generous with their bug reports and feature

00:45:35.239 --> 00:45:39.120
requests and reporting how things work on different platforms.

00:45:39.120 --> 00:45:49.760
So to conclude, go forth and engage in very precise code-heavy conversations about R.

00:45:49.800 --> 00:45:55.080
I'm going to take a look at the questions now.

00:45:55.080 --> 00:45:59.479
Okay, okay.

00:45:59.479 --> 00:46:01.679
So I can see these, you cannot.

