00:46:06.879 --> 00:46:13.320
Can reprex be able to also capture variables in the environment and include in the reproducible

00:46:13.320 --> 00:46:15.199
example?

00:46:15.199 --> 00:46:26.199
Currently it cannot, and that is very intentional because we really prioritize this sandboxing.

00:46:26.199 --> 00:46:33.439
I am actually contemplating basically creating a backdoor for this, mostly because of creating

00:46:33.439 --> 00:46:39.639
RTF snippets, but at the moment it cannot, and that is intentional, but you know, I'm

00:46:39.639 --> 00:46:44.479
open to people sharing their use case about why that should be.

00:46:44.479 --> 00:46:51.239
But basically if you do this, yeah, there are ways you could do it that actually make

00:46:51.239 --> 00:46:55.040
those objects available to other people as well, but it becomes a much heavier weight

00:46:55.040 --> 00:46:56.040
package.

00:46:56.040 --> 00:46:58.239
So, so far we have not done that.

00:46:58.239 --> 00:47:04.679
Oftentimes, I think this is a continuation of that question, the issue is buried in some

00:47:04.679 --> 00:47:10.159
part of larger code, and rather than going back to the places where that data is gathered

00:47:10.159 --> 00:47:14.280
or calculated, wouldn't it be nice to grab the variable in the current state?

00:47:14.280 --> 00:47:22.360
Again, like yes and no, I would say extracting that out is perhaps part of your job.

00:47:22.360 --> 00:47:28.120
Oh, I'm now realizing that some of these questions have been answered.

00:47:28.120 --> 00:47:33.239
Does reprex, the function, actually check that the code is self-contained, or does it

00:47:33.239 --> 00:47:35.560
just generate a template?

00:47:35.560 --> 00:47:38.239
It just generates a template.

00:47:38.320 --> 00:47:46.840
So, the way you would find out that your code is not self-contained is that you get an error.

00:47:46.840 --> 00:47:52.760
But it explicitly allows errors, because sometimes you're using reprex to show errors, so no,

00:47:52.760 --> 00:48:00.239
it is just, it's on you, the human, to decide if you're getting the result you expect.

00:48:00.239 --> 00:48:09.639
Let's see.

00:48:09.639 --> 00:48:15.120
Does readr, readcsv, support the text argument as an alternative to file, or is that only

00:48:15.120 --> 00:48:17.040
